  Welsh  ,   Walsh  . The idea that the Scottish surname refers to the Welsh-speaking Britons of Strathclyde is erroneous."],"variants":[{"name":"Wallace","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Wallis  , especially in Scotland, where the name was introduced from the Welsh Marches by a family of tenants of the Stewarts in the 12th century.","Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish (Ashkenazic) surnames, e.g.   Wallach  ."]},{"name":"Wales","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Wales near Sheffield (South Yorkshire). The placename means ‘The Welshmen’ and denoted a settlement of Brittonic speakers living on the boundary between the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms of Northumbria and Mercia (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). See also   Wallis  .","habitational name from Wales, the country named from Old English <i>wēalas</i> ‘foreigners’ (especially those speaking Celtic or Romance languages). This meaning of the surname is quite rare."]},{"name":"Welsh","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish: ethnic name from Middle English <i>welshe</i> (Old English <i>wēalisc</i>, <i>wēlisc</i>) ‘foreign, Welsh’, for someone from Wales or a speaker of the Welsh language. Compare   Walsh   and   Wallace  .","Americanized form of German   Welsch  .","Americanized form of Ukrainian and Jewish (from Ukraine)   Voloshin   or its Polish variant <b>Wołoszyn</b> (see   Woloszyn  )."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Ralph Wallis was born about 1600, in Scotland. She had at least 1 son with Ralph Wallen."},"et":{"about 1600–":"umbes 1600–Surnud","1590–1633":"1590–1633","1619–1685":"1619–1685","1600–Female":"1600–Surnud","1600":"1600","1633":"1633","1685":"1685","about 1600":"umbes 1600","1619":"1619","1590":"1590","Scotland":"Scotland","London, England":"London, England"},"fi":{"about 1600–":"noin 1600–Kuollut","1590–1633":"1590–1633","1619–1685":"1619–1685","1600–Female":"1600–Kuollut","1600":"1600","1633":"1633","1685":"1685","about 1600":"noin 1600","1619":"1619","1590":"1590","Scotland":"Scotland","London, England":"London, England"},"fr":{"about 1600–":"environ 1600–Décédée","1590–1633":"1590–1633","1619–1685":"1619–1685","1600–Female":"1600–Décédée","1600":"1600","1633":"1633","1685":"1685","about 1600":"environ 1600","1619":"1619","1590":"1590","Scotland":"Écosse","London, England":"Londres, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Ralph Wallis est née environ 1600, à Écosse. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Ralph Wallen."},"de":{"about 1600–":"um 1600–Verstorben","1590–1633":"1590–1633","1619–1685":"1619–1685","1600–Female":"1600–Verstorben","1600":"1600","1633":"1633","1685":"1685","about 1600":"um 1600","1619":"1619","1590":"1590","Scotland":"Scotland","London, England":"London, England","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Ralph Wallis wurde um 1600 in Scotland geboren. Sie hatte mit Ralph Wallen mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1600–":"about 1600–Desede","1590–1633":"1590–1633","1619–1685":"1619–1685","1600–Female":"1600–Desede","1600":"1600","1633":"1633","1685":"1685","about 1600":"about 1600","1619":"1619","1590":"1590","Scotland":"Scotland","London, England":"London, England"}